text: I'm so excited for this! A Dog's Purpose/Journey is one of my favorite books. I really liked the first movie, but it felt a lot more fast-paced than the book (understandably, there was a lot to fit in). But A Dog's Journey, the book, felt more fast paced than Purpose (not necessarily in a good way). The movie, based on this trailer, really helps visualize the story better, I think. Of course, they also changed the story line quite a bit, but I like the change (especially -- SPOILER: given that Ethan dies at the end of the first book, so A Dog's Journey is all about CJ; I like that they kept Ethan in it). Anyway, I'm really looking forward to seeing this.

text: Somehow, this series reinforces to me the notion that the line of dogs I'm close to were all incarnations of my beloved Lacy. She was my baby sister since 4th grade until she died just when I graduated from high school. On the day I went back to visit my high school buddy's house the year after, there was a new dog to their pack named Buster. Somehow, Buster just came up to me and gave me a paw-hug like he knew me. I was at my high school buddy's place all the time, and Buster was always specifically close to me. Strangely, Buster looked a lot like Lacy. Years later, after I moved away from my home town, my next door neighbor in my new city adopted two pups who I hang out with all the time. One, in particular named Piper, seemed to have begun life likely around the same time Buster would've died. Strangely, Piper is very much like Lacy and Buster, and she's my best little friend in this town. Weird....  By the way, I'm glad Hollywood has gotten the message regarding Asian American diversification, especially regarding Asian American men. Studio knows how to draw in certain audiences, I see.

text: My dog (Princess) died because of parvovirus months ago. She was the cutest chihuahua we had. She loved to lay down on her food. My grandma took her out for a walk. When they went home, Princess didn't felt good. She wasn't as energetic as last time. She loved to bite my leg and bark at nothing. But all she did was sleep. Few days later and she tried pooping. I thought it was normal poop at first, but it was blood. We took Princess to the vet to check her out. The vet said that there's a 50% chance of her living. I was praying. Praying to God hoping she'd live. Unfortunately, She died. My grandma cried because she was her favorite dog. We buried her outside our house. Few months passed, my dog (Quincy who is a Chihuahua. We had 6 dogs that time) gave birth to 3 dogs. The other one didn't make it. Only 2 of them were alive. One of them is a boy and the other is a girl. We named the boy Peanut since the first dog that we gave was Peanut. We gave Peanut away because we needed money that time. We named the girl Princess because she looked like The original Princess that died. That got me wondering, what if Princess is Princess? The 2nd Princess is hyperactive too like the original Princess. They both look alike, and loved to bark at nothing. But I don't think that's possible.

text: My dog of 16 1/2 years left me as held his paws 2 years ago and you have no idea how bad I'd wish this would happen to me. Funny thing is it kind of did but in a different way. My dogs birthday was the 4th of July. On that day last year it would have been 2 years since his passing and I was missing him more than ever. Well, up walks this grey Cat (i didnt know at the time but she was a russian blue) and she just comes walking up the driveway, into the garage and onto my lap. She wanted nothing more than to be loved but she was very skittish and was almost like she was afraid because she didn't know exactly what love was. So I started leaving food out for her and she would come up the driveway every day at the same time and every morning when I got home from work. Cut to two weeks later and she is slowly trying to come to the front door. Cut to a week later from that and she brings her nose to the tip of the door. A week later she puts part of her nose in the house and the week after that half of her body. That took about two months of letting her get used to my smells and eventually she started coming in the house to eat. About a month after that she was in the house for good and didn't want to leave but occasionally we would let her outside to get her smells and come back. A few days after that I let her outside and did not know it but there was a stray cat across the street and Bam just like that she got pregnant. So I snatched her up put her in the house and nine months later I am at work working midnights and get a phone call that I have for kittens in the closet. I did not know it at the time but I would be raising three kittens because one passed at Birth which happens occasionally and now I have a mother and one of her kittens and was able to foster two kittens to the same house. the only way I can explain it is it was almost like a sign from above that my dog knew I was missing him terribly and he sent her to me. Or at least thats how im seeing it.

text: We adopted a kitten after the passing of a family cat.  A volunteer from the cat rescue brought the kitten to our home to check us out and see how the first meeting went with the kitten.  Before she opened the crate she said that the kitten was  from a single floor home and never saw stairs.  She warned that the kitten would probably be afraid and hide under furniture.  The kitten was released into our house and went right up our stairs, went directly to my daughter's bedroom, jumped on the bed where the old cat like to be.  The kitten had a look on her face like I am home!  The pet adoption volunteer never saw anything like it.

text: My dog that I had since I was 7 passed away yesterday morning.  His name was Buddy Love and I'm really excited to see this movie. I already watched A Dogs Purpose and loved it.  It made me feel so much better. With the little strength Buddy had left he came in my room and fell down. I gave him my pillow and blankets.  Buddy was my world and I feel so guilty because I didn't know what to do. I stood next to him trying to keep myself together. I told him if he goes to heaven there will be a big bed that he can lay on and he can eat whatever he wants and he can run in a field with Sadie. (My stepmoms dog that sadly got hit by a car) and he can look down on us anytime he wants and then I told him if he get's reborn I hope he has the best life with love and laughter. And then I brought up our amazing journey that we had together. As I'm typing I'm crying. He was always there for me when I was sad, Lonley or angry. I love you so much Buddy Love. I'm so sorry you had to suffer but I hope that you're in a better place now. And I pray that you can hear me when I need you. We love all love and miss you and we will forever keep you in our hearts and I'll think about you everyday of my life.
author: Scotty A Burns

author: Hornytoad

text: So how many kids and families has this immortal dog been forced to live with and how can he possibly remember, let alone love any of them?  And if he loves them, does he not live in an unending hell where he is forced to die again and again and watch others die again and again, trapped in a relentless cycle of karmic pain. Does he not scream for release with every fiber of his being or perhaps he is just cold, like ice, feeling nothing for all eternity.
author: Hornytoad

text: Pets are fine but pet-worship is just a mental disorder affecting people who have serious trouble socializing and who are psychologically or neurologically incapable of bonding properly with other humans. That's why you don't find it in traditional communities and cultures with strong family structures, only in disaffected, dysfunctional, atomized modern urban landscapes.  It is a side-effect of modern life, a symptom of alienation.  it also why worshiping pets has nothing to do with caring for animals or wildlife generally, and nothing to do with the environment: it is entirely selfish; an emotional crutch.
author: Hornytoad

text: Yesterday my dog died and I’m soo sad I wish my dog can just com back to life. When I heard that he passed away I was already crying and then when I saw his dead body for the first time, i was crying so much. It was a sad horrible sight. His name is tikki and he is a chihuahua and died from old age. He’s the same age as me (13) and I’m about to turn 14. When I saw his dead body, I saw tears come from his eyes and before he died, he cried for help. My mom went but it was to late. He was crying and it was so sad when he died. He pretty much died alone and I just wish we were there for him. He was one of my first family and my friend. I just wish he was here. He died on June 4 2019 at 3pm. 5 or 6 hours later we buried him. It was so sad having our family and friends gather around burying him. It was so sad. On the same exact day, we even gave him a shower that morning and my sister got a cute picture of that cute old dog. I already miss him and can’t stop thinking about him. The amount of likes this comment gets is the amount of respect payed. Ima try to visit his grave often which is in my backyard.

text: Rainbow Bridge  Just this side of heaven is a place called Rainbow Bridge.   When an animal dies that has been especially close to someone here, that pet goes to Rainbow Bridge.  There are meadows and hills for all of our special friends so they can run and play together.  There is plenty of food, water and sunshine, and our friends are warm and comfortable.   All the animals who had been ill and old are restored to health and vigor; those who were hurt or maimed are made whole and strong again, just as we remember them in our dreams of days and times gone by.  The animals are happy and content, except for one small thing; they each miss someone very special to them, who had to be left behind.   They all run and play together, but the day comes when one suddenly stops and looks into the distance. His bright eyes are intent; His eager body quivers. Suddenly he begins to run from the group, flying over the green grass, his legs carrying him faster and faster.   You have been spotted, and when you and your special friend finally meet, you cling together in joyous reunion, never to be parted again. The happy kisses rain upon your face; your hands again caress the beloved head, and you look once more into the trusting eyes of your pet, so long gone from your life but never absent from your heart.   Then you cross Rainbow Bridge together.
author: Kaegan Thornhill

text: I just screened A Dogs Journey again, but this time with the directors commentary [Gail Mancuso...] on, and I have to say that this film in a very short time has become one of my all time favorite movies. A Dog's Purpose had me in tears most of the time, as my own dog is really starting to show her age and slow down, and although we got her out of a kill shelter back in 2010, as she was a to be destroyed dog - almost 10 years later now, I can honestly say that my life is forever changed by this one rescue dog, who in turn rescued me. During A Dog's Purpose, I started to wonder what my dog's purpose was... and it is possible that it is now leading somewhere or to someone I would have otherwise not ever met.... But I have to say that A Dogs Journey was so good - not only as a sequal, but as a stand alone  movie, as everything - the cast, the dogs, the filming, the music... it was all just right, and as a whole absolutely perfect. Gail Mancuso, outstanding job.... BRAVO !!!

text: I’ve lost a dog that’s looks like a breed of Bailey in the movie. He succumbed to parvo at the age of 8 years (56 dog years). Now I grew up, I went to a shelter for dogs and got a dog who wasn’t really interested in me or my gf. But we had to put him down due to complications. Got another dog and I remembered something from my last dog when I was little that got my attention. My old dog used to jump high and loved to bark when you respond to him. The dog I currently have and adopted did the same thing my childhood dog did, bark when responding and jumps to you. Ugh! And this movie made me cry because dogs do have a lifetime to find their owners over again. My dog, I love her to death no matter what 😌
